Mitigating damages due to a cyber attack in industrial plants relies upon timely triage of early physical process symptoms. This aims to connect process symptoms to a potential control host intrusion. Unfortunately, due to the semantic gap between host and process behavior, operators must manually and painstakingly iterate between diverse control host and process forensic logs. This slows down their response, is error-prone, and may lead to further damage. We present PhyLink, a post-mortem technique to automatically connect process symptoms to control host intrusion, allowing operators to respond to confirmed attacks and stop damages. PhyLink uses physical evidence (e.g., device symptom location) to guide a symbolic binary exploration of the control host execution context (from memory snapshots). Learning from past control host attacks, PhyLink develops a generic approach to not only link host intrusion vectors to process symptoms, but ranks them by their likelihood to cause damages. This helps operators prioritize their response (e.g., which symptoms to respond to). Using 1219 real-world control host snapshots, we evaluated PhyLink against past attacks, and adaptive attacks to evade PhyLink. We show that PhyLink is robust in triaging control host-originated process attacks.